<!DOCTYPE html><html><head><meta charset="utf-8"><title>Meta-analysis Report</title><style>body{font-family:Calibri,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:11pt;line-height:1.5;margin:1in;}h1{font-size:20pt;margin:0 0 10pt;}h2{font-size:14pt;margin:16pt 0 8pt;}p{margin:0 0 8pt;white-space:pre-wrap;}</style></head><body><h1>META-ANALYSIS REPORT</h1><p><strong>Generated by Pairwise Pro v2.2</strong><br>2026-03-05T20:56:40.384Z</p><h2>Methods</h2><p>Statistical Analysis</p><p>We performed a pairwise meta-analysis following established methodological guidelines. Effect sizes were expressed as odds ratios on the natural logarithm scale for analysis, then back-transformed for presentation. A random-effects model was used to account for expected clinical and methodological heterogeneity across studies. Between-study variance (tau-squared) was estimated using the DerSimonian-Laird estimator. Confidence intervals were calculated using the Hartung-Knapp-Sidik-Jonkman (HKSJ) adjustment, which provides improved coverage when the number of studies is small.</p><p>Heterogeneity was quantified using the I-squared statistic (proportion of variability due to heterogeneity rather than sampling error), tau-squared (absolute between-study variance), and Cochran Q test. We calculated 95% prediction intervals to estimate the range of effects expected in future similar settings. Publication bias was assessed visually using funnel plots and statistically using Egger regression test. Sensitivity analyses included leave-one-out analysis to identify influential studies. All analyses were conducted using Pairwise Pro v2.2, with results validated against the metafor package in R.</p><p>Novel Validated Pairwise Methods</p><p>We additionally ran a validated advanced methods pack comprising RoBMA posterior model averaging (Monte Carlo); exact beta-binomial rare-event synthesis; robust t random-effects meta-analysis; sequential monitoring (TSA + Bayesian); Egger regression with cluster-robust variance.</p><h2>Results</h2><p>Main Results</p><p>A total of 6 studies met inclusion criteria, comprising 73,431 participants with 1,006 events.</p><p>The pooled odds ratio was OR = 0.37 (95% CI: 0.23 to 0.61; p=&lt;0.001), indicating a statistically significant reduction. This corresponds to a 63% relative reduction in risk.</p><p>The 95% prediction interval ranged from 0.08 to 1.76, crossing the null value, indicating that effects in future similar settings may vary from beneficial to harmful.</p><p>Heterogeneity</p><p>Statistical heterogeneity was high. The I-squared statistic was 84.8% (95% CI: 68.8% to 92.6%), indicating that the majority of observed variance reflected true differences between studies. The between-study variance was tau-squared = 0.2510 (tau = 0.501, corresponding to approximately 65% typical variation in effects on the ratio scale). Cochran Q test: Q = 32.97, df = 5, p=&lt;0.001 (significant).</p><p>Publication Bias</p><p>Visual inspection of the funnel plot did not reveal obvious asymmetry. Egger regression test was not significant (intercept = -3.610, SE = 4.004, p=0.4182), providing no strong evidence of publication bias. Peters test (less affected by heterogeneity): p=N/A.</p><p>Trim-and-fill analysis imputed 0 potentially missing studies.</p><p>Cross-Disciplinary Robustness Checks</p><p>The PDG scale-factor analysis gave S = 2.57. Confidence intervals were inflation-adjusted by 156.8% for excess dispersion.</p><p>The low-I2 diagnostic was classified as HETEROGENEITY DETECTED (power to detect I2=25%: 76%; disagreeing study pairs: 26.7%).</p><p>Winner's-curse diagnostics suggested Minimal inflation detected. Bias-adjusted consensus estimate: OR = 0.45.</p><p>Response-distribution modeling estimated P(benefit)=97.6%, P(MCID)=95.3%, and P(harm/no-benefit)=2.4% in future settings.</p><p>Novel Validated Pairwise Analyses</p><p>RoBMA posterior pooled theta = -0.9890 (95% interval -1.4831 to -0.4973); posterior model probability of bias mechanisms = 0.0%.</p><p>Rare-event exact synthesis estimated OR = 0.368 (95% interval 0.286 to 0.472); P(OR&lt;1) = 100.0%.</p><p>Robust t random-effects model estimated theta = -1.0027, tau2 = 0.1467, p=&lt;0.001.</p><p>Sequential monitoring first crossed TSA boundary at k=3 and Bayesian decision threshold at k=3.</p><p>Egger-RVE intercept p-value = 0.3482 across 6 clusters.</p><h2>TruthCert Verdict</h2><p>TruthCert Evidence Verdict</p><p>          EXPOSED</p><p>          </p><p>            Tier C | Severity: 7/13</p><p>          </p><p>        </p><p>      </p><p>              </p><p>                ⚠️ Severity Assessment ?</p><p>                </p><p>                  </p><p>        7</p><p>      </p><p>                  Extreme heterogeneity +1Publication bias +1Low breakdown point +1Low fragility +1PI crosses null +1Permutation conflict +1Multiple influential +1</p><p>                </p><p>              </p><p>              </p><p>                🛡️ 12-Point Threat Ledger ?</p><p>                </p><p>                  </p><p>          ✓</p><p>          Evidence Base6 studies (min: 4)</p><p>        </p><p>          ✓</p><p>          Estimator AgreementSpread: 0.0471 (Î´: 0.1054)</p><p>        </p><p>          ✗</p><p>          HeterogeneityI² = 84.8%</p><p>        </p><p>          ✓</p><p>          τ² StabilityEstimates converge</p><p>        </p><p>          ✗</p><p>          Publication BiasPeters: p = 0.031</p><p>        </p><p>          ✗</p><p>          Breakdown Robustness0% to flip</p><p>        </p><p>          ✗</p><p>          Fragility IndexN/A (non-binary)</p><p>        </p><p>          !</p><p>          Prediction Interval[-2.541, 0.566]</p><p>        </p><p>          !</p><p>          Permutation CI[-0.916, 0.916]</p><p>        </p><p>          !</p><p>          Influence5 influential studies</p><p>        </p><p>          ✓</p><p>          RoB SensitivityStable</p><p>        </p><p>          ✓</p><p>          OIS Status14427% of required</p><p>        </p><p>         